{"title_page": "Cage the Elephant discography", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist          = [[Cage the Elephant]]\n| Image           = Cagetheelephant in 2008 1.jpg\n| Caption         = [[Matt Shultz|Matthew Shultz]] of Cage the Elephant performing at the London Barfly in March 2008\n| Alt             = A long-haired Caucasian man sings into a microphone, illuminated in a red light.\n| Studio          = 5\n| Live            = 2\n| EP              = 1\n| Singles         = 16\n| Music videos    = 17\n}}\n\nThe discography of American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Cage the Elephant]] consists of five [[studio album]]s, one [[live album]], one [[extended play]], 16 [[Single (music)|single]]s and 17 [[music video]]s. The band released [[Cage the Elephant|their self-titled debut album]] in June 2008. It peaked at number 59 on the United States [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and at number 18 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard charts|Top Alternative Albums]] chart.<ref name=\"US-albums\"/><ref name=\"US-Alternative-albums\"/> The album has been certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref name=\"Cage the Elephant album sales\"/><ref name=\"RIAA\"/> \"[[Ain't No Rest for the Wicked]]\", the album's third single, peaked at number 83 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and became a top 50 hit in Canada and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"US-singles\"/><ref name=\"CAN-singles\"/><ref name=\"UK-singles\"/> The singles \"[[In One Ear (song)|In One Ear]]\" and \"[[Back Against the Wall (song)|Back Against the Wall]]\" both topped the ''Billboard'' [[Alternative Songs]] chart.<ref name=\"US-Alternative-singles\"/>\n\n''[[Thank You, Happy Birthday]]'', the band's second studio album, was released in January 2011. It peaked at number two on the ''Billboard'' 200, as well as on the Top Alternative Albums and [[Billboard charts|Top Rock Albums]] charts.<ref name=\"US-albums\"/><ref name=\"US-Alternative-albums\"/><ref name=\"US-Rock-albums\"/> \"[[Shake Me Down]]\", the album's lead single, peaked at number 78 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and became the band's third number-one hit on the Alternative Songs chart.<ref name=\"US-singles\"/><ref name=\"US-Alternative-singles\"/> The album's remaining singles\u2014\"[[Around My Head]]\", \"[[Aberdeen (song)|Aberdeen]]\" and \"Always Something\"\u2014all entered the latter chart.<ref name=\"US-Alternative-singles\"/>\n\nTheir third album ''[[Melophobia]]'' (2013) featured the hit singles \"[[Cigarette Daydreams]]\" and \"[[Come a Little Closer (Cage the Elephant song)|Come a Little Closer]]\".\n\nIn 2015, they released their fourth studio album ''[[Tell Me I'm Pretty]]''. \"[[Mess Around (Cage the Elephant song)|Mess Around]]\", \"[[Trouble (Cage the Elephant song)|Trouble]]\" and \"[[Cold Cold Cold]]\" were all released as singles.\n\nOn November 26, 2018, they announced their fifth studio album, ''[[Social Cues]]'', which was released on April 19, 2019.\n\n==Albums==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with selected chart positions, sales figures and certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:9em;\"| Sales\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref name=\"US-albums\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/cage-the-elephant/chart-history/billboard-200 |title=Cage the Elephant Chart History: Billboard 200 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Billboard charts|US<br />Alt.]]<br /><ref name=\"US-Alternative-albums\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/cage-the-elephant/chart-history/alternative-albums |title=Cage the Elephant Chart History: Alternative Albums |work=Billboard |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Billboard charts|US<br />Rock]]<br /><ref name=\"US-Rock-albums\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/cage-the-elephant/chart-history/rock-albums |title=Cage the Elephant Chart History: Rock Albums |work=Billboard |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL]]<br /><ref name=\"BEL (FL)\">{{cite web | url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Cage+The+Elephant | title=Discografie Cage the Elephant | work=ultratop.be | accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br /><ref name=\"CAN-albums\">Peak chart positions for albums in Canada:\n* All except noted: {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/cage-the-elephant/chart-history/canadian-albums |title=Cage the Elephant Chart History: Canadian Albums |work=Billboard |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}\n* ''Cage the Elephant'': {{cite web|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Charts/ALBUMS.html |title=Albums: Top 100 (For The Week Ending 25 August, 2011) |work=[[Jam!]] |date=September 1, 2011 |accessdate=August 26, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61D6vrdk3?url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Charts/ALBUMS.html|archivedate=August 25, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|FRA]]<br><ref name=\"FRA\">* ''Social Cues'': {{cite web|url=http://www.snepmusique.com/tops-semaine/top-album-megafusion/?ye=2019&we=17|title=Le Top de la semaine : Top Albums \u2013 SNEP (Week 17, 2019)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref>\