, workers|last=Ngcakani|first=Noluthando|date=2020-03-16|website=Food For Mzansi|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Wimpy (restaurant)|Wimpy]] [[Lifesaving South Africa]], national championships cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/wimpy-lifesaving-south-africa-national-championships-cancelled-44956403|title=Wimpy Lifesaving South Africa National Championships cancelled|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Scouts South Africa]], all Scouting activity suspended until schools reopen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scouts.org.za/2020/03/16/scouting-suspended-in-response-to-covid-19/|title=Scouting suspended in response to COVID-19|website=www.scouts.org.za|date=16 March 2020|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[Johannesburg|City of Johannesburg]], all public facilities closed indefinitely including public swimming pools, recreational and civic centres, stadiums, libraries, sporting facilities, and the [[Johannesburg Zoo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2257497/city-of-joburg-closes-all-public-facilities-including-pools-theatres-and-the-zoo/|title=City of Joburg closes all public facilities, including pools, theatres and the zoo |agency=News24 Wire |website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[EThekwini Metropolitan Municipality|Ethekhwini Metropolitan Municipality]] closed all of [[Durban]]'s public facilities including swimming pools, beaches, libraries, community halls, and museums while restrictions have been put in place for the [[Durban Art Gallery]] and cemeteries to only allow 50 people at a time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/lifestyle/383319/durban-bans-swimming-at-the-beach/|title=Durban bans swimming at the beach|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n*[[Fake news]] spread to the effect that [[5G|5G cellular]] technology was the true cause of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] symptoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/lifestyle/technology/2263396/zweli-mkhize-says-5g-causing-covid-19-deaths-is-just-fake-news/|title=Zweli Mkhize says \u20185G causing Covid-19 deaths\u2019 is just fake news|last=Cilliers|first=Charles|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Economic impact===\nAt the beginning of the national shutdown on the 27 March South African economists predicted that the pandemic could cause a 2.5% to 10% contraction of [[Economy of South Africa|South Africa's total GDP]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/economy/sa-economy-could-crater-up-to-10-this-year/|title=SA economy could crater up to 10% this year|date=2020-03-25|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The national lockdown and resulting economic slowdown reduced demand for electricity by more than 7 500 MW thereby temporarily reducing the impact of the long running [[South African energy crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/eskom-will-keep-the-lights-on-during-21-day-lockdown-45708578\n|title=Eskom will keep the lights on during 21-day lockdown\n|date=2020-03-28\n|publisher=Independent Media\n|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n====Stock market news====\nThe [[JSE Limited|JSE]] lost 15% of its value in the week ending 13 March 2020, its worst week in 21 years.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/markets/2020-03-13-market-wrap-jse-has-worst-week-since-1998-as-pandemic-plagues-investors/\n|title=MARKET WRAP: JSE has worst week since 1998 as pandemic plagues investors\n|date=2020-03-13\n|first1=Odwa\n|last1=Mjo\n|work=BusinessLIVE\n|accessdate=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[South African Reserve Bank]] governor, [[Lesetja Kganyago]] announced a reduction of the country's [[Repurchase agreement|repo rate]] by 100 basis points or 1 percentage point to 5.25%.<ref name=\"RepoSlashed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/south-africa/live-repo-rate-decision/|title=Repo rate slashed by 1%|last=Mar 2020|first=Suren Naidoo / 19|date=2020-03-19|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n====Banking and retail====\nRetailers like Clicks, [[Pick n Pay Stores|Pick n Pay]], and [[Woolworths Holdings Limited|Woolworths]] have some limitations on the number of the same items customers may buy.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/cornonavirus-linked-panic-buying-retailers-ration-stock-2020-3\n|title=Woolworths stops food demonstrations, limits items per customer - here's what other retailers are doing\n|date=2020-03-19\n|first1=Jay\n|last1=Caboz\n|publisher=Business Insider\n|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 19 March, [[Minister of Trade and Industry (South Africa)|Minister of Trade and Industry]] [[Ebrahim Patel]] signed a government gazette that enforces [[price controls]] on essential items and that could see [[Price gouging|price gougers]] punished with measures including a R10 million fine, a fine equivalent to 10% of a firm's turnover, or [[Imprisonment|12 months in prison]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/business/383217/new-regulations-bring-coronavirus-price-controls-for-certain-high-demand-products-heres-what-is-on-the-list/|title=New regulations bring coronavirus price controls for certain high-demand products \u2013 here's what is on the list|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Standard Bank]] announced a 90-day [[Forbearance|payment holiday]] for small and medium-sized business and students to try and shield them from the economic impact of the outbreak, starting from 1 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/coronavirus-standard-bank-gives-businesses-a-debt-holiday-2020-3|title=Coronavirus: Standard Bank gives businesses, students a debt holiday|website=BusinessInsider|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Misinformation ==\n{{Main|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe arrival of the COVID 19 virus in South Africa saw an increase in the dissemination of misinformation about the virus on social media and other platforms. These range from messages minimising the virus's harm in the country<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-31-viral-outbreak-fake-news-spreads-in-sa-in-tandem-with-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus Fact Check#1: Viral outbreak: Fake news spreads in SA in tandem with Covid-19|last=Davis|first=Rebecca|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> to the propagation of [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] about government actions to control the virus.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/fake-news-no-covid-19-testing-kits-are-not-contaminated-20200406|title=FAKE NEWS: No, Covid-19 testing kits are not contaminated|last=|first=|date=2020-04-06|website=News24|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>  The spreading of [[fake news]] and other misinformation in South Africa about the virus is an offence punishable with either a fine, six months\u2019 imprisonment, or both.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nOne individual was arrested for posting a video showing himself drinking in public with friends following the national lockdown whilst stating that there was \u201cnothing called corona here\u201d.<ref name=\":0\" /> In another incident a man claimed that 10,000 government officials would be going door-to-door using contaminated test kits to test people for the virus.<ref name=\":1\" /> A conspiracy theory that [[Bill Gates]] wished to test a Covid 19 \u201cvaccine\u201d in Africa or South Africa first caused significant controversy on social media<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-04-06-bill-gates-trevor-noah-death-threats--that-vaccine-how-it-all-went-wrong/|title=Bill Gates, Trevor Noah, death threats & that vaccine: how it all went wrong|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> following the publication of a now retracted story in [[News24]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/apology-to-the-bill-and-melinda-gates-foundation-for-africa-vaccine-story-20200405|title=Apology to the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation for 'Africa vaccine' story|date=2020-04-05|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> and [[The South African]], [[Trevor Noah]] stated that he received hate mail for conducting the interview with Gates where it was falsely reported that Gates made the claim.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|South Africa|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.gov.za/taxonomy/term/707 South African government statements]\n*[http://www.nicd.ac.za/media/ NICD media]\n*[https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) outbreak]\n*[https://sacoronavirus.co.za/ Official government website for information about Coronavirus in South Africa]\n*[https://t.me/CoronaZABot Corona Telegram Bot for South Africa]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jeandr\u00e9 du Toit", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:04-06 c1686 d12 nicd1686stats", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Africa"}
{"title_page": "Brian Blume", "text_new": "{{short description|American game designer, writer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Brian John Blume\n| image        =\n| alt          =\n| caption      =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1950|01|12|mf=y}}<ref name=\"TSR #5\"/>\n| birth_place  = [[Oak Park, Illinois]], [[United States]]<ref name=obituary />\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|2020|03|27|1950|01|12}}\n| death_place  = [[Elkhorn, Wisconsin]], [[United States]]\n| occupation   = Writer, game designer\n| spouse         = Victoria Miller\n| nationality  = [[United States]]\n| period       =\n| genre        = [[Role-playing game]]s, [[fantasy]], [[Wargaming|wargames]]\n| influences   =\n| portaldisp   =\n}}\n\n'''Brian John Blume''' (January 12, 1950 \u2013 March 27, 2020)<ref name=obituary /> was a game designer and writer, principally known as a former business partner of [[Gary Gygax]] at [[TSR, Inc.]], producers of the [[fantasy]] [[role-playing game]] ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]''.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life ===\nBrian Blume was born January 12, 1950, in [[Oak Park, Illinois]] to Melvin and Kathleen Blume,<ref name=\"obituary\">{{cite web | url = https://www.haaselockwoodfhs.com/obituary/Brian-Blume| title = Obituary for Brian John Blume | accessdate = March 31, 2020| date = March 31, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331164123/https://www.haaselockwoodfhs.com/obituary/Brian-Blume|archivedate=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"TSR #5\">{{cite journal  | last =  Kask | first = Tim  | authorlink =  Tim Kask | coauthors =   | title = In the Cauldron  | journal = [[Dragon (magazine)|The Strategic Review]]  | volume =  | issue = #5  | pages = 2, 8  | publisher = TSR, Inc.  | location = [[Lake Geneva, Wisconsin]]  | date = December 1975  | url =   | format =  | accessdate = }}</ref> and grew up in [[Wauconda, Illinois]] with four brothers and three half-brothers.<ref name=obituary /> Blume began playing chess at age seven, and ''[[Gettysburg (game)|Gettysburg]]'' at age nine. \n\nHe was fascinated by history in junior high school and was involved in [[miniature wargaming]] in high school. After graduating as class valedictorian, Blume attended [[Wabash College]],<ref name=obituary /> but left to become a [[tool and die]] making [[journeyman]] for his father's company for five years.<ref name=\"TSR #5\"/><ref name=\"inc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.inc.com/magazine/19820201/3601.html|title=TSR Hobbies Mixes Fact and Fantasy|date=1982-02-01|author=Stewart Alsop II}}</ref>\n\n===''Dungeons & Dragons'' and TSR===\nBlume met [[Gary Gygax]] at the [[Gen Con]] [[game convention]] in [[Lake Geneva]], [[Wisconsin]]. Gygax and his friend [[Don Kaye]] had recently formed [[Tactical Studies Rules]] in Lake Geneva in order to publish a new type of game that Gygax and [[Dave Arneson]] had developed, ''Dungeons & Dragons''. Gygax and Kaye had each invested $1,000 into the venture but still did not have enough money to print the game. In December 1973, Blume offered to become an equal partner in the company for an investment of $2,000.<ref name=\"playingworld\">{{cite book|title=Playing at the World|last=Peterson|first=Jon|publisher=Unreason Press|year=2012|isbn=978-0-615-64204-8|location=San Diego|pages=|oclc=808727087}}</ref>{{Rp|78}} Using Blume's money, the three partners printed a thousand copies of the new game and sold their first copy in January 1974. Blume and Gygax also co-authored the ''[[Warriors of Mars (game)|Warriors of Mars]]'' miniatures wargame adaptation. Before the end of 1974, the first printing of ''D&D'' had sold out, and demand for the game was skyrocketing. \n\nJust as the young company was gearing up to meet demand, unexpected disaster struck. Don Kaye, although only 36, suddenly died of a heart attack.<ref name=\"wired\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/gaming/virtualworlds/news/2008/03/ff_gygax?currentPage=all |title=Dungeon Master: The Life and Legacy of Gary Gygax |publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |last=Kushner |first=David |date=2008-03-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113190652/http://www.wired.com/gaming/virtualworlds/news/2008/03/ff_gygax?currentPage=all |archivedate=2012-11-13 }}</ref> Kaye had not made any specific provision in his will regarding his one-third share of the company, so his share of TSR passed to his wife Donna. In July 1975, Gygax and Blume reorganized their company from a partnership to a corporation called TSR Hobbies, with Gygax as president. Gygax owned 150 shares, Blume owned the other 100 shares, and both had the option to buy up to 700 shares at any time in the future. But TSR Hobbies had nothing to publish \u2014 ''D&D'' was still owned by the three-way partnership of Tactical Studies Rules, and neither Gygax nor Blume had the money to buy out the share owned by Donna Kaye. Blume persuaded a reluctant Gygax to allow his father, Melvin Blume, to buy Donna's share, and that was converted to 200 shares in TSR Hobbies.<ref name=\"uiwgg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thekyngdoms.com/forums/viewtopic.php?t=37|title=The Ultimate Interview with Gary Gygax|website=The Kyngdoms|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404124008/http://www.thekyngdoms.com/interviews/garygygax.php|archive-date=April 4, 2016|url-status=dead|accessdate=June 7, 2016}}</ref> In addition, Brian bought another 140 shares.<ref name=\"witwer\">{{cite book|title=Empire of the Imagination: Gary Gygax and the Birth of Dungeons & Dragons|last=Witwer|first=Michael|date=2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-63286-279-2|location=New York|pages=|oclc=908838677}}</ref>{{rp|117}} The Blumes and Gygax formed the company's three-person board.<ref name=\"designers\">{{cite book|title=Designers & Dragons|last=Appelcline|first=Shannon|publisher=Mongoose Publishing|year=2011|isbn=978-1-907702-58-7|location=|pages=}}</ref>{{rp|7}} \n\nShortly afterward, Blume received a blind mailing of the first issue of the monthly newsletter ''[[Owl and Weasel]]'' from [[Games Workshop]], recently formed by [[Ian Livingstone]] and [[Steve Jackson (UK game designer)|Steve Jackson]]. In return, Blume sent them a copy of ''Dungeons & Dragons''. Livingstone and Jackson felt that this game was more imaginative than anything being produced in the UK at the time, so they worked out an arrangement with Blume for a three-year exclusive deal to sell ''D&D'' in [[Europe]].<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|43}}\n\nAs various new rules and products for ''D&D'' were created,  Blume provided material for ''[[The Rogues Gallery]]'',<ref>Blume, Brian, [[David Cook (game designer)|David Cook]], and [[Jean Wells]], ''[[The Rogues Gallery]]''. (TSR, 1980)</ref> and co-authored the ''Dungeons & Dragons'' supplement ''[[Eldritch Wizardry]]'' with Gygax in 1976,<ref>Gygax, Gary and Brian Blume. ''[[Eldritch Wizardry|Supplement III: Eldritch Wizardry]]'' (TSR, 1976)</ref> naming the character [[Vecna]] as an anagram of [[Jack Vance]]. Blume and Gygax also co-authored the ''[[Boot Hill (role-playing game)|Boot Hill]]'' role-playing game as a tribute to Don Kaye, who had been a fan of [[Westerns]].<ref name=\"believer\">{{cite journal | last = La Farge | first = Paul | title = Destroy All Monsters | journal = [[The Believer Magazine]] | date = September 2006 | url = http://www.believermag.com/issues/200609/?read=article_lafarge | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080920141500/http://www.believermag.com/issues/200609/?read=article_lafarge | url-status = dead | archivedate = 2008-09-20 | access-date = 2008-12-25 }}</ref><ref>Blume, Brian, and Gary Gygax. ''Boot Hill'' (TSR, 1975)</ref> Blume also authored the ''[[Panzer Warfare]]'' miniatures wargame in 1975.\n\n===Power struggle within TSR===\nBrian met Victoria Miller and married her in 1980.<ref name=obituary /> \n\nAt about the same time, Blume persuaded Gygax to allow Blume's brother Kevin to purchase Melvin Blume's 200 shares. By 1981, the Blume brothers were increasingly unhappy with Gygax's conservative approach to the business, so using their greater stock ownership, they effectively took control by splitting TSR Hobbies into TSR, Inc., and TSR Entertainment, Inc.<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|13}}  While Kevin Blume became president of TSR, Inc., Gygax was made president of TSR Entertainment, Inc.,<ref name=\"Dragon #103\">{{cite journal | title = TSR Profiles | journal = [[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]] | issue = #103 | page = 56 | publisher = TSR, Inc. | location = [[Lake Geneva, Wisconsin]] | date = November 1985}}</ref> and the Blumes sent him to Hollywood to develop TV and movie opportunities.<ref name=designers />{{rp|13}} \n\nBank creditors insisted on the appointment of three independent directors with business experience,<ref name=\"ambush\">{{cite web| url=https://medium.com/@increment/the-ambush-at-sheridan-springs-3a29d07f6836 | title=The Ambush at Sheridan Springs| last = Peterson | first = Jon| date = 2014-07-28 | accessdate=2018-11-15}}</ref> so the Blumes brought in three outside directors from the [[American Management Association]] \u2013 a lawyer from a large Milwaukee firm, a personnel officer from a Milwaukee area company, and an owner of a company that made medical equipment \u2013 to enlarge the Board of Directors to six people. None of the new directors knew anything about gaming, but they always voted with the Blumes.<ref name=\"believer\"/><ref name=\"Kyngdoms\">{{Cite web | last = Sacco | first = Ciro Alessandro | title = The Ultimate Interview with Gary Gygax | work = thekyngdoms.com | url = http://www.thekyngdoms.com/forums/viewtopic.php?t=37 | accessdate = 2008-10-24 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120208133710/http://www.thekyngdoms.com/forums/viewtopic.php?t=37 | archive-date = 2012-02-08 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nWith Gygax gone, the Blumes were free to move TSR Inc. into new directions. After TSR acquired [[Simulation Publications|SPI]] in March 1982, the Blumes declared that they had \"bought assets but not liabilities\". Actually, SPI owed money to their printers, who refused to release the plates for printing SPI's games until TSR repaid SPI's bills.<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|14}} On a more successful note, the Blumes moved into the book trade with popular series such as ''[[Endless Quest]]''.<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|14}} The Blumes also moved into toy manufacturing, metal miniatures, and even the [[needlecraft]] business.<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|15}} In the company's main business of role-playing games, the Blumes oversaw the creation of the new role-playing lines ''[[Dragonlance]]'' and ''[[Marvel Super Heroes (role-playing game)|Marvel Super Heroes]]''.<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|16}} However, all of these new ventures were expensive, and by 1984, although TSR Inc. was the games industry leader, grossing $30 million, it was barely breaking even and had debts of $1.5 million. The Blume brothers began to shop around for someone to buy the company.<ref name=witwer />{{rp|171}}   \n\nWhen Gygax heard that TSR was being shopped around, he returned to Lake Geneva. After some investigation of the company finances, Gygax charged that the financial crisis was due to mismanagement by Kevin Blume: excess inventory, overstaffing, too many company cars, and some questionable (and expensive) projects such as dredging up a 19th-century shipwreck.<ref name=witwer />{{rp|172}} Gygax persuaded the board of directors to remove Kevin Blume as president.<ref name=\"believer\"/> The final vote was 4\u20131, with Brian Blume abstaining.<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|16}} However, the outside directors still believed the company's financial problems were terminal and the company needed to be sold. In an effort to prevent this, in March 1985 Gygax exercised his 700-share stock option, giving him just over 50% control. He appointed himself president and CEO, and in order to bring some financial stability to TSR, he hired a company manager, [[Lorraine Williams]],<ref name=\"believer\"/> who dismissed the three outside directors.<ref name=\"Kyngdoms\"/> Bringing Williams on board backfired for Gygax when in October 1985, Brian Blume revealed that he had triggered his own 560-share option, and then he and his brother Kevin had sold all their shares to Williams, leaving her as the majority shareholder. Gygax took TSR to court in a bid to block the Blumes' sale of their shares to Williams, but he lost,<ref name=\"gamespy2.1\">{{cite web|url=http://pc.gamespy.com/articles/538/538820p1.html|title=Gary Gygax Interview \u2013 Part 2 (page 1)|accessdate=October 3, 2008|date=August 16, 2004 |last=Rausch|first=Allen|work=[[GameSpy]]|publisher=IGN Entertainment|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917181104/http://pc.gamespy.com/articles/538/538820p1.html |archivedate=September 17, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and Williams replaced Gygax as president and CEO.\n\nHaving sold all his company shares, Brian Blume stepped down from the board of directors and left TSR.<ref name=\"believer\"/>\n\n===Subsequent game work===\nBlume later worked as a [[cartographer]], making maps for numerous [[White Wolf, Inc.|White Wolf]] supplements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pen-paper.net/rpgdb.php?op=showcreator&creatorid=645|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050426063103/http://www.pen-paper.net/rpgdb.php?op=showcreator&creatorid=645|archivedate=April 26, 2005|title=Pen & Paper listing for Brian Blume|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Later Life===\nBlume died on March 27, 2020, at the Lakeland Nursing Home in [[Elkhorn, Wisconsin]] from [[Lewy Body Dementia]] and [[Parkinson's disease]].<ref name=obituary />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{D&D topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blume, Brian}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dungeons & Dragons game designers]]\n[[Category:Role-playing game designers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American game designer, writer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Brian John Blume\n| image        =\n| alt          =\n| caption      =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1950|01|12|mf=y}}<ref name=\"TSR #5\"/>\n| birth_place  = [[Oak Park, Illinois]], [[United States]]<ref name=obituary />\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|2020|03|27|1950|01|12}}\n| death_place  = [[Elkhorn, Wisconsin]], [[United States]]\n| occupation   = Writer, game designer\n| spouse         = Victoria Miller\n| nationality  = [[United States]]\n| period       =\n| genre        = [[Role-playing game]]s, [[fantasy]], [[Wargaming|wargames]]\n| influences   =\n| portaldisp   =\n}}\n\n'''Brian John Blume''' (January 12, 1950 \u2013 March 27, 2020)<ref name=obituary /> was a game designer and writer, principally known as a former business partner of [[Gary Gygax]] at [[TSR, Inc.]], producers of the [[fantasy]] [[role-playing game]] ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]''.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life ===\nBrian Blume was born January 12, 1950, in [[Oak Park, Illinois]] to Melvin and Kathleen Blume,<ref name=\"obituary\">{{cite web | url = https://www.haaselockwoodfhs.com/obituary/Brian-Blume| title = Obituary for Brian John Blume | accessdate = March 31, 2020| date = March 31, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331164123/https://www.haaselockwoodfhs.com/obituary/Brian-Blume|archivedate=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"TSR #5\">{{cite journal  | last =  Kask | first = Tim  | authorlink =  Tim Kask | coauthors =   | title = In the Cauldron  | journal = [[Dragon (magazine)|The Strategic Review]]  | volume =  | issue = #5  | pages = 2, 8  | publisher = TSR, Inc.  | location = [[Lake Geneva, Wisconsin]]  | date = December 1975  | url =   | format =  | accessdate = }}</ref> and grew up in [[Wauconda, Illinois]] with four brothers and three half-brothers.<ref name=obituary /> Blume began playing chess at age seven, and ''[[Gettysburg (game)|Gettysburg]]'' at age nine. \n\nHe was fascinated by history in junior high school and was involved in [[miniature wargaming]] in high school. After graduating as class valedictorian, Blume attended [[Wabash College]],<ref name=obituary /> but left to become a [[tool and die]] making [[journeyman]] for his father's company for five years.<ref name=\"TSR #5\"/><ref name=\"inc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.inc.com/magazine/19820201/3601.html|title=TSR Hobbies Mixes Fact and Fantasy|date=1982-02-01|author=Stewart Alsop II}}</ref>\n\n===''Dungeons & Dragons'' and TSR===\nBlume met [[Gary Gygax]] at the [[Gen Con]] [[game convention]] in [[Lake Geneva]], [[Wisconsin]]. Gygax and his friend [[Don Kaye]] had recently formed [[Tactical Studies Rules]] in Lake Geneva in order to publish a new type of game that Gygax and [[Dave Arneson]] had developed, ''Dungeons & Dragons''. Gygax and Kaye had each invested $1,000 into the venture but still did not have enough money to print the game. In December 1973, Blume offered to become an equal partner in the company for an investment of $2,000.<ref name=\"playingworld\">{{cite book|title=Playing at the World|last=Peterson|first=Jon|publisher=Unreason Press|year=2012|isbn=978-0-615-64204-8|location=San Diego|pages=|oclc=808727087}}</ref>{{Rp|78}} Using Blume's money, the three partners printed a thousand copies of the new game and sold their first copy in January 1974. Blume and Gygax also co-authored the ''[[Warriors of Mars (game)|Warriors of Mars]]'' miniatures wargame adaptation. Before the end of 1974, the first printing of ''D&D'' had sold out, and demand for the game was skyrocketing. \n\nJust as the young company was gearing up to meet demand, unexpected disaster struck. Don Kaye, although only 36, suddenly died of a heart attack.<ref name=\"wired\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/gaming/virtualworlds/news/2008/03/ff_gygax?currentPage=all |title=Dungeon Master: The Life and Legacy of Gary Gygax |publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |last=Kushner |first=David |date=2008-03-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113190652/http://www.wired.com/gaming/virtualworlds/news/2008/03/ff_gygax?currentPage=all |archivedate=2012-11-13 }}</ref> Kaye had not made any specific provision in his will regarding his one-third share of the company, so his share of TSR passed to his wife Donna. In July 1975, Gygax and Blume reorganized their company from a partnership to a corporation called TSR Hobbies, with Gygax as president. Gygax owned 150 shares, Blume owned the other 100 shares, and both had the option to buy up to 700 shares at any time in the future. But TSR Hobbies had nothing to publish \u2014 ''D&D'' was still owned by the three-way partnership of Tactical Studies Rules, and neither Gygax nor Blume had the money to buy out the share owned by Donna Kaye. Blume persuaded a reluctant Gygax to allow his father, Melvin Blume, to buy Donna's share, and that was converted to 200 shares in TSR Hobbies.<ref name=\"uiwgg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thekyngdoms.com/forums/viewtopic.php?t=37|title=The Ultimate Interview with Gary Gygax|website=The Kyngdoms|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404124008/http://www.thekyngdoms.com/interviews/garygygax.php|archive-date=April 4, 2016|url-status=dead|accessdate=June 7, 2016}}</ref> In addition, Brian bought another 140 shares.<ref name=\"witwer\">{{cite book|title=Empire of the Imagination: Gary Gygax and the Birth of Dungeons & Dragons|last=Witwer|first=Michael|date=2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-63286-279-2|location=New York|pages=|oclc=908838677}}</ref>{{rp|117}} The Blumes and Gygax formed the company's three-person board.<ref name=\"designers\">{{cite book|title=Designers & Dragons|last=Appelcline|first=Shannon|publisher=Mongoose Publishing|year=2011|isbn=978-1-907702-58-7|location=|pages=}}</ref>{{rp|7}} \n\nShortly afterward, Blume received a blind mailing of the first issue of the monthly newsletter ''[[Owl and Weasel]]'' from [[Games Workshop]], recently formed by [[Ian Livingstone]] and [[Steve Jackson (UK game designer)|Steve Jackson]]. In return, Blume sent them a copy of ''Dungeons & Dragons''. Livingstone and Jackson felt that this game was more imaginative than anything being produced in the UK at the time, so they worked out an arrangement with Blume for a three-year exclusive deal to sell ''D&D'' in [[Europe]].<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|43}}\n\nAs various new rules and products for ''D&D'' were created,  Blume provided material for ''[[The Rogues Gallery]]'',<ref>Blume, Brian, [[David Cook (game designer)|David Cook]], and [[Jean Wells]], ''[[The Rogues Gallery]]''. (TSR, 1980)</ref> and co-authored the ''Dungeons & Dragons'' supplement ''[[Eldritch Wizardry]]'' with Gygax in 1976,<ref>Gygax, Gary and Brian Blume. ''[[Eldritch Wizardry|Supplement III: Eldritch Wizardry]]'' (TSR, 1976)</ref> naming the character [[Vecna]] as an anagram of [[Jack Vance]]. Blume and Gygax also co-authored the ''[[Boot Hill (role-playing game)|Boot Hill]]'' role-playing game as a tribute to Don Kaye, who had been a fan of [[Westerns]].<ref name=\"believer\">{{cite journal | last = La Farge | first = Paul | title = Destroy All Monsters | journal = [[The Believer Magazine]] | date = September 2006 | url = http://www.believermag.com/issues/200609/?read=article_lafarge | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080920141500/http://www.believermag.com/issues/200609/?read=article_lafarge | url-status = dead | archivedate = 2008-09-20 | access-date = 2008-12-25 }}</ref><ref>Blume, Brian, and Gary Gygax. ''Boot Hill'' (TSR, 1975)</ref> Blume also authored the ''[[Panzer Warfare]]'' miniatures wargame in 1975.\n\n===Power struggle within TSR===\nBrian met Victoria Miller and married her in 1980.<ref name=obituary /> \n\nAt about the same time, Blume persuaded Gygax to allow Blume's brother Kevin to purchase Melvin Blume's 200 shares. By 1981, the Blume brothers were increasingly unhappy with Gygax's conservative approach to the business, so using their greater stock ownership, they effectively took control by splitting TSR Hobbies into TSR, Inc., and TSR Entertainment, Inc.<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|13}}  While Kevin Blume became president of TSR, Inc., Gygax was made president of TSR Entertainment, Inc.,<ref name=\"Dragon #103\">{{cite journal | title = TSR Profiles | journal = [[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]] | issue = #103 | page = 56 | publisher = TSR, Inc. | location = [[Lake Geneva, Wisconsin]] | date = November 1985}}</ref> and the Blumes sent him to Hollywood to develop TV and movie opportunities.<ref name=designers />{{rp|13}} \n\nBank creditors insisted on the appointment of three independent directors with business experience,<ref name=\"ambush\">{{cite web| url=https://medium.com/@increment/the-ambush-at-sheridan-springs-3a29d07f6836 | title=The Ambush at Sheridan Springs| last = Peterson | first = Jon| date = 2014-07-28 | accessdate=2018-11-15}}</ref> so the Blumes brought in three outside directors from the [[American Management Association]] \u2013 a lawyer from a large Milwaukee firm, a personnel officer from a Milwaukee area company, and an owner of a company that made medical equipment \u2013 to enlarge the Board of Directors to six people. None of the new directors knew anything about gaming, but they always voted with the Blumes.<ref name=\"believer\"/><ref name=\"Kyngdoms\">{{Cite web | last = Sacco | first = Ciro Alessandro | title = The Ultimate Interview with Gary Gygax | work = thekyngdoms.com | url = http://www.thekyngdoms.com/forums/viewtopic.php?t=37 | accessdate = 2008-10-24 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120208133710/http://www.thekyngdoms.com/forums/viewtopic.php?t=37 | archive-date = 2012-02-08 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nWith Gygax gone, the Blumes were free to move TSR Inc. into new directions. After TSR acquired [[Simulation Publications|SPI]] in March 1982, the Blumes declared that they had \"bought assets but not liabilities\". Actually, SPI owed money to their printers, who refused to release the plates for printing SPI's games until TSR repaid SPI's bills.<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|14}} On a more successful note, the Blumes moved into the book trade with popular series such as ''[[Endless Quest]]''.<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|14}} The Blumes also moved into toy manufacturing, metal miniatures, and even the [[needlecraft]] business.<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|15}} In the company's main business of role-playing games, the Blumes oversaw the creation of the new role-playing lines ''[[Dragonlance]]'' and ''[[Marvel Super Heroes (role-playing game)|Marvel Super Heroes]]''.<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|16}} However, all of these new ventures were expensive, and by 1984, although TSR Inc. was the games industry leader, grossing $30 million, it was barely breaking even and had debts of $1.5 million. The Blume brothers began to shop around for someone to buy the company.<ref name=witwer />{{rp|171}}   \n\nWhen Gygax heard that TSR was being shopped around, he returned to Lake Geneva. After some investigation of the company finances, Gygax charged that the financial crisis was due to mismanagement by Kevin Blume: excess inventory, overstaffing, too many company cars, and some questionable (and expensive) projects such as dredging up a 19th-century shipwreck.<ref name=witwer />{{rp|172}} Gygax persuaded the board of directors to remove Kevin Blume as president.<ref name=\"believer\"/> The final vote was 4\u20131, with Brian Blume, abstaining.<ref name=\"designers\"/>{{rp|16}} However, the outside directors still believed the company's financial problems were terminal and the company needed to be sold. In an effort to prevent this, in March 1985 Gygax exercised his 700-share stock option, giving him just over 50% control. He appointed himself president and CEO, and in order to bring some financial stability to TSR, he hired a company manager, [[Lorraine Williams]],<ref name=\"believer\"/> who dismissed the three outside directors.<ref name=\"Kyngdoms\"/> Bringing Williams on board backfired for Gygax when in October 1985, Brian Blume revealed that he had triggered his own 560-share option, and then he and his brother Kevin had sold all their shares to Williams, leaving her as the majority shareholder. Gygax took TSR to court in a bid to block the Blumes' sale of their shares to Williams, but he lost,<ref name=\"gamespy2.1\">{{cite web|url=http://pc.gamespy.com/articles/538/538820p1.html|title=Gary Gygax Interview \u2013 Part 2 (page 1)|accessdate=October 3, 2008|date=August 16, 2004 |last=Rausch|first=Allen|work=[[GameSpy]]|publisher=IGN Entertainment|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917181104/http://pc.gamespy.com/articles/538/538820p1.html |archivedate=September 17, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and Williams replaced Gygax as president and CEO.\n\nHaving sold all his company shares, Brian Blume stepped down from the board of directors and left TSR.<ref name=\"believer\"/>\n\n===Subsequent game work===\nBlume later worked as a [[cartographer]], making maps for numerous [[White Wolf, Inc.|White Wolf]] supplements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pen-paper.net/rpgdb.php?op=showcreator&creatorid=645|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050426063103/http://www.pen-paper.net/rpgdb.php?op=showcreator&creatorid=645|archivedate=April 26, 2005|title=Pen & Paper listing for Brian Blume|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Later Life===\nBlume died on March 27, 2020, at the Lakeland Nursing Home in [[Elkhorn, Wisconsin]] from [[Lewy Body Dementia]] and [[Parkinson's disease]].<ref name=obituary />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{D&D topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blume, Brian}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dungeons & Dragons game designers]]\n[[Category:Role-playing game designers]]\n", "name_user": "Guinness323", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePower struggle within TSR:remove comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Blume"}
{"title_page": "Aarushi Sharma", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| image        = \n| caption      =\n| name         =  '''Aarushi Sharma'''\n| birth_date   =  {{birth date and age|1996|01|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[New Delhi]], [[India]]\n|measurements =\n| occupation   = [[Actor]]\n| education    = [[Amity University, Noida]]\n| residence    = [[Delhi]], [[New Delhi]]\n| religion     = \n| height       = {{convert|5|ft|06|in|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"fmd\">{{cite web|url=http://beautypageants.indiatimes.com/contestants/2015/aarushi-sharma/contestantprofile/49090663.cms|title= Aarushi Sharma|publisher=Indiatimes.com}}</ref>\n| haircolour   = Brown<ref name=\"fmd\"/>\n| eyecolour    = Hazel Brown<ref name=\"fmd\"/>\n| title        = Miss Intercontinental India 2016\n| competitions = Miss Intercontinental India 2016<br/>(Winner)<br/>[[Miss Diva - 2015]]<br/>(Finalist)<br/>(Miss Body Beautiful - Top 5)<br/>(Miss Internet - Top 3)<br/>[[Femina Miss India|Campus Princess 2015]]<br/>(Finalist)\n| website       = \n}}\n\n'''Aarushi Sharma''' is an [[India]]n actor and pageant titleholder from [[New Delhi]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}  She participated in the third edition of [[Miss Diva|Miss Diva - 2015]] in 2015 and was selected as a finalist.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yamaha Facino Miss Diva 2015 launch grand affair|url=http://m.beautypageants.in/miss-diva/yamaha-fascino-miss-diva-2016-launch-was-a-grand-affair/eventshow/52603756.cms|date=20 April 2016|newspaper= The Times Of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Miss Diva 2015/Resui - Urvashi Rautela crowned as Miss Diva Universe 2015|url=http://www.india.com/showbiz/yamaha-fascino-miss-diva-2016-finale-bengaluru-beauty-roshmitha-harimurthy-wins-the-title-1480527/|date=20 April 2015|publisher= India Times}}</ref> In 2016, she participated in [[Miss International|Senorita India]] pageant and won the crown of Miss Intercontinental India 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senorita India 2016 Full Results|url=http://thegreatpageantcommunity.com/2016/09/12/rewati-chetri-wins-senorita-india-2016-full-results/|date=12 September 2016|publisher=The Pageant Community}}</ref> She represented India at the Miss Intercontinental 2016 held in [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Miss Intercontinental 2016 - Meet the contestants|url=http://www.missintercontinental.com/about/|date=26 April 2016|publisher=Miss Intercontinental Official Page|website=}}</ref> She has featured in several Punjabi music videos since early 2017 such as Aa Chak Challa by Sajjan Adeeb,<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X7CTDA6z9Vo</ref> Ik Vaar by Kanwar Chahal,<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mvkvXrEV6-8</ref> Hath Chumme by Ammy virk.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y1ixFdnkITg</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film \n! Character\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Kaka Ji]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Kaka Ji Debut Punjabi Movie|url=https://sirfjatt.com/album/kaka-ji-himmat-sandhu-hvbrh-songs.html|date=22 January 2019|newspaper= SirfJatt.Com}}</ref>\n| Deepi\n| Debut film released on 18 January 2019\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''High End Yaariyaan''\n| Celina\n| Released on 22 February 2019\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2020\n|-\n|Love Aaj Kal\n|Leena\n|Released on 14 February 2020\n|-\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Song Title\n! Singer\n! Director\n! Record label\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2017\n|Taqdeer\n|Azam Aulakh\n|Dilsher Singh & Khuspal Singh\n|Lokdhun Punjabi\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Aa Chak Challa''<ref>https://sirfjatt.com</ref> \n| Sajjan Adeeb\n| Dilsher Singh & Khushpal Singh\n| Speed Records\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Ik Vaar ''\n| Kanwar Chahal\n| Dilsher Singh & Khushpal Singh\n| [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Pagg Wali Selfie ''\n| Preet Harpal\n| TeamDG\n| [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n|\n|-\n|